\section{MANUAL SPECIFICS}\label{MANUAL SPECIFICS}

\subsection{List of manuals to be published}

The only manuals I would definitely exclude in the first instance are the tutorial overheads.

There are some which are very small, though probably none too small to be publishable by the
available technology.

The following table shows the USR documents, their proposed titles (dropping capitalisation and adjusting tutorial names) and current lengths.
The leftmost column indicates a proposed volume-in-series number.
A gap ni the series numbers has been left after each reference manual in case it should ever prove necessary to split the manual over two volumes.
The titles which have been change are those for USR004, 5, 11, 13, 29 and 30.

The \emph{pub} column show whether publication from the existing PDF files appears to be technically
feasible, and is either y for ``yes'', n for ``no'' (only for documents of less than 24 pages),
or s for ``conditional on shrink'',
``Conditional on shrink'' means that the page count exceeds the maximum for the closest to A4 print
size (8.5 x 11 inches), which is 630, but may be publishable by re-printing from the A4 PDF to a PDF at a smaller size using Adobe Acrobat (7.44 by 9.69\" seems to work with a page limit of 828).
Amazon provides a shrink to fit facility which is more sophisticated, but it gives bad results on the first page of our manuals.

