\paragraph{Title Credits}

Certain credit must, and others may, appear in the title information associated
with the registration of the ISBN.
The credits here are not necessarily the same as credits shown on the cover or the
interior of the book, but are used in the pages used on amazon and {\bf create}space web sites.

It is desirable I think to keep the credits shown here to a moderate number,
which in the case of the ProofPower manuals suggests that not all contributors to
a manual should be listed.

By way of compromise I suggest that the following credits are shown:

\begin{itemize}
\item the principal author (see below)
\item for the 2 reference manuals credit to Roger Stokes for the index
\item for each volume, credit to Roger Jones as ``series editor''
\end{itemize}

A more comprehensive attribution of credit might also list under
``contributions by'' all the contributors to the manual, or perhaps
all who made more than some threshold number of commits.

The following table is compiled using git shortlog to determine the
number of commits, and a certain amount of common sense
(major contributions may be introduced by a single commit,
and the reference manuals are compiled primarily from information
stripped from dtds and therefore a log of the top level document
is misleading as to the origins of the bulk of the material).

The code significance is as follows:
p
\begin{description}
\item[A] Principal Author
\item[a] Author
\item[C] Contributions by
\item[I] Index by
\item[P] Prepared for publication by
\end{description}

The numbers appearing in the table are the number of commits
by the author to the volume.

I have placed the author attributions primarily using my own
guess about who the principle author is.
I doubt that a commit threshold would give a sensible set of
additional contribution credits.
If the threshold were 10 for example, there would be only a
small number of such attributions, but they would include
crediting both Rob Arthan and Roger Jones with contributions
to USR004 which I'm not convinced is warranted.


